Here's the approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

Create three XAML files (e.g., in a `Themes/` folder):

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
    <!-- ... -->
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` using the same keys but different values.

### 2. Build a theme-switching service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDicts.Clear();

        mergedDicts.Add(theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Themes.LightTheme(),
        });

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

### 3. Apply the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
}
```

### 4. Reference theme keys with `DynamicResource`

This is critical — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}"
           Text="Hello, themed world!" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 5. Wire up the settings page

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var selected = (AppTheme)ThemePicker.SelectedIndex;
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- Same resource keys across all three dictionaries — only the values differ.
- Always use `DynamicResource` so swapping the dictionary updates the UI instantly.
- `Preferences` persists the choice across app restarts.
